Note:
PowerShell→HIR Translator - Translate PowerShell AST to HIR

This file provides translation from PowerShell Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)
to High-level Intermediate Representation (HIR) for universal language
translation through the Translation system.

Features:
- Complete PowerShell AST → HIR translation
- Preserves cmdlet-specific semantics
- Cmdlet and parameter translation
- Pipeline translation
- Control structure translation (if, while, for, foreach, switch)
- Function/class definition translation
- Variable assignment and reference translation
- Exception handling translation (try-catch-finally)
- Object-oriented feature translation

HIR Format:
- Dictionaries for structured data
- Lists for collections
- Preserves all semantic information for bidirectional translation

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_core.runa (HIR operations)
- frontends/powershell/powershell_parser.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/powershell/powershell_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/powershell/powershell_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/hashtable.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR Dictionary and List Operations (REAL IMPLEMENTATIONS)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Thin facade over hashtable_create so call sites in this module consistently
use HIR-oriented vocabulary ("create_hir_dict") instead of the underlying
collection primitive name. The wrapper costs one extra call per allocation
but keeps the translator's source uniform with the other create_hir_*
helpers; renaming the primitive would break every other consumer of Dict.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates directly to Dict.hashtable_create with no arguments and returns
its result unchanged.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_hir_dict" returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR dictionary using real hashtable

    Return proc hashtable_create from Dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin facade over list_create so call sites consistently say
"create_hir_list" - keeping HIR terminology at the call sites
rather than dictionary/list primitive names. Wrapping costs one
extra call but keeps the rest of the file vocabulary-consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to List.list_create and returns its result directly.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_hir_list" returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR list using real dynamic list

    Return proc list_create from List
End Process

@Reasoning:
Facade over hashtable_set so call sites use the HIR-oriented name
set_dict_value rather than the primitive's name. Same intent as
the create_* wrappers - vocabulary consistency.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to Dict.hashtable_set with the same arguments and
returns its result.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_dict_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set dictionary value using real hashtable_set

    Return proc hashtable_set from Dict with dict, key, value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Naming-only wrapper over list_push so call sites read "list_append"
matching the conventional dictionary/list verbiage used elsewhere
in the translator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to List.list_push and returns its result.
@End Implementation
Process called "list_append" takes list as Integer, item as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Append item to list using real list_push

    Return proc list_push from List with list, item
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named-string accessor. Same underlying hashtable_get as
get_dict_hir_value but with a name that documents the expected
value kind at the call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to Dict.hashtable_get and returns its result.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_dict_string_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get string value from dictionary using real hashtable_get

    Return proc hashtable_get from Dict with dict, key
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named-HIR-node accessor. Same underlying hashtable_get; the
distinct name signals that the value should be interpreted as a
nested HIR dictionary by the caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to Dict.hashtable_get and returns its result.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_dict_hir_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get HIR value from dictionary using real hashtable_get

    Return proc hashtable_get from Dict with dict, key
End Process

@Reasoning:
Vocabulary wrapper over list_length matching the create_hir_list /
list_append naming convention.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to List.list_length and returns its result.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_list_count" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get list count using real list_length

    Return proc list_length from List with list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Vocabulary wrapper over list_get keeping the consistent HIR
vocabulary across the translator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to List.list_get with the index and returns its result.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_list_item" takes list as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get list item using real list_get

    Return proc list_get from List with list, index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PowerShell AST → HIR Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
PowerShell literals come in four AST kinds (string=80, number=81,
boolean=82, null=83) sharing the same shape: a "value" pointer at
offset 8 plus a node_type at offset 0. This translator dispatches
on the type tag and emits a discriminated HIR literal so the
backend can pick the right format on emission. Each literal type
preserves the original value pointer rather than re-parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for a null ast. Reads node_type (offset 0) and value
(offset 8). Creates an empty HIR dict. Matches node_type:
- 80 -> "string_literal" with value
- 81 -> "number_literal" with value
- 82 -> "boolean_literal" with value
- 83 -> "null_literal" with value
Each branch sets the dict's node_type and value keys then returns
the dict immediately. If none match, returns the empty dict (no
_type key) so the caller can detect the unknown literal.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_literal" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate literal values (string, number, boolean) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32

    Let hir_node be proc create_hir_dict

    Note: AST_STRING_LITERAL (72)
    If node_type is equal to 72:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "string_literal"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Note: AST_NUMBER_LITERAL (73)
    If node_type is equal to 73:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "number_literal"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Note: AST_BOOLEAN_LITERAL (74)
    If node_type is equal to 74:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "boolean_literal"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Note: AST_NULL_LITERAL (75)
    If node_type is equal to 75:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "null_literal"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Note: AST_IDENTIFIER (70) — used for member/method/type/parameter names,
    Note: which the literal-style consumers in the backend read under "value".
    If node_type is equal to 70:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "identifier"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell variable references `$name` carry just the name (no
scope prefix is parsed here - scope qualifiers like `$global:` or
`$script:` are part of the name string from the parser). HIR
encodes it as a variable_reference dict for downstream lookup
resolution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads value (offset 8) as the variable
name. Builds an HIR dict with node_type="variable_reference" and
name=value. Returns the dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_variable" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell variable ($variable) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32

    Let hir_var be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_var, "node_type", "variable_reference"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_var, "name", value

    Return hir_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell parameters `-Name Value` carry the parameter name as
first child and an optional value as second. The name is always a
literal (translate_literal); the value can be any expression and
recurses through translate_node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads children (offset 32) and child_count
(offset 40). Builds HIR dict with node_type="parameter". If
child_count > 0 takes children[0] as the name, runs through
translate_literal, stores under "name". If child_count > 1 takes
children[8] as the value, runs through translate_node, stores
under "value". Returns the dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_parameter" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell parameter (-Parameter) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note:
    The parser emits AST_PARAMETER in two shapes:
      1. Cmdlet named argument `-Name value`: the name lexeme (without the
         leading dash) is in the value slot (offset 32) and the optional
         value expression is the first child.
      2. Declaration `[Type]$name = default`: the value slot is empty; the
         children are an optional type expression (AST_TYPE_EXPRESSION = 46),
         the variable (AST_VARIABLE = 32) carrying the name in its own value
         slot, and an optional default value (any other node).
    Both shapes resolve to a name node (read by the backend as name ->
    "value") plus an optional value subtree.
    :End Note
    Let name_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_param be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "node_type", "parameter"

    Note: Determine whether the value slot carries a usable name.
    Let has_name_value be 0
    If name_value is not equal to 0:
        Let name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with name_value
        If name_len is greater than 0:
            Set has_name_value to 1
        End If
    End If

    If has_name_value is equal to 1:
        Note: Shape 1: cmdlet named argument.
        Let name_hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with name_hir, "node_type", "identifier"
        proc set_dict_value with name_hir, "value", name_value
        proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "name", name_hir

        If child_count is greater than 0:
            Let value_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
            Let value_hir be proc translate_node with value_ast
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "value", value_hir
        End If

        Return hir_param
    End If

    Note: Shape 2: declaration. Walk the children once, classifying each by
    Note: its AST tag, to extract the variable name and the default value.
    Let var_name be ""
    Let default_ast be 0
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than child_count:
        Let child_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, j multiplied by 8
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_ast, 0

        If child_type is equal to 32:
            Note: AST_VARIABLE — the parameter name (stripped of its $).
            Set var_name to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_ast, 32
        Otherwise:
            If child_type is equal to 46:
                Note: AST_TYPE_EXPRESSION — type annotation; not needed for the
                Note: name/value the backend emits, so skipped here.
                Set j to j
            Otherwise:
                Note: Any other node is the default value expression.
                Set default_ast to child_ast
            End If
        End If

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Let decl_name_hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with decl_name_hir, "node_type", "identifier"
    proc set_dict_value with decl_name_hir, "value", var_name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "name", decl_name_hir

    If default_ast is not equal to 0:
        Let default_hir be proc translate_node with default_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "value", default_hir
    End If

    Return hir_param
End Process

@Reasoning:
A cmdlet reference (e.g. Get-ChildItem) is just a name; no
arguments are attached at this level. Parameters and arguments
hang off the parent AST_CMDLET_INVOCATION. Keeping cmdlets as a
separate node lets the HIR distinguish a bare cmdlet reference
(e.g. as a callable expression) from an invocation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads value (offset 8) as the cmdlet
name. Builds HIR dict with node_type="cmdlet" and name=value.
Returns the dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_cmdlet" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell cmdlet (verb-noun commands) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32

    Let hir_cmdlet be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_cmdlet, "node_type", "cmdlet"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_cmdlet, "name", value

    Return hir_cmdlet
End Process

@Reasoning:
A cmdlet invocation `Get-ChildItem -Path C:\ "filter"` is the
cmdlet plus a mix of parameters (named, AST_PARAMETER=72) and
positional arguments (any other AST). The translator routes each
child to the right list by reading its AST tag so the resulting
HIR cleanly separates "parameters" from "arguments".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads children and child_count. Builds
HIR dict with node_type="cmdlet_invocation". If child_count > 0
takes children[0] (the cmdlet AST), runs through translate_cmdlet,
stores under "cmdlet". Creates empty parameters and arguments
lists. Iterates index i from 1 to child_count-1: reads each
child, then its node_type (offset 0). If 72 (AST_PARAMETER) calls
translate_parameter and appends to parameters; otherwise calls
translate_node and appends to arguments. Stores both lists under
"parameters" and "arguments" keys.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_cmdlet_invocation" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell cmdlet invocation with parameters to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: The parser models a cmdlet invocation as a single AST_CMDLET node:
    Note: the Verb-Noun name is stored in the node value slot (offset 32) and
    Note: every argument / named parameter follows as a child (offset 16).
    Let name_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_invocation be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_invocation, "node_type", "cmdlet_invocation"

    Note: Build the cmdlet name node (the backend reads "cmdlet" -> "name").
    Let cmdlet_hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with cmdlet_hir, "node_type", "cmdlet"
    proc set_dict_value with cmdlet_hir, "name", name_value
    proc set_dict_value with hir_invocation, "cmdlet", cmdlet_hir

    Note: Parameters and arguments
    Let parameters be proc create_hir_list
    Let arguments be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_ast, 0

        Note: AST_PARAMETER (31) is a named parameter; everything else is a
        Note: positional argument.
        If child_type is equal to 31:
            Let param_hir be proc translate_parameter with child_ast
            proc list_append with parameters, param_hir
        Otherwise:
            Let arg_hir be proc translate_node with child_ast
            proc list_append with arguments, arg_hir
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_invocation, "parameters", parameters
    proc set_dict_value with hir_invocation, "arguments", arguments

    Return hir_invocation
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell pipelines `cmd1 | cmd2 | cmd3` are ordered chains of
commands. The HIR encodes them as a list of recursively-translated
command HIRs under "commands" so downstream backends can emit
the equivalent piped invocation in their target language.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "pipeline".
Iterates children 0..child_count-1, calls translate_node on each,
appends to the commands list. Stores commands under "commands".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_pipeline" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell pipeline (cmd1 | cmd2 | cmd3) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_pipeline be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_pipeline, "node_type", "pipeline"

    Let commands be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let cmd_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let cmd_hir be proc translate_node with cmd_ast
        proc list_append with commands, cmd_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_pipeline, "commands", commands

    Return hir_pipeline
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell array literals `@(1, 2, 3)` collect every element as a
sibling child. The HIR uses an "elements" list under
array_literal. Both `@()` (explicit array) and inline
comma-separated forms route here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "array_literal".
Iterates children, recursively translates each, appends to
elements list stored under "elements".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_array_literal" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell array @() to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_array be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_array, "node_type", "array_literal"

    Let elements be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let element_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let element_hir be proc translate_node with element_ast
        proc list_append with elements, element_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_array, "elements", elements

    Return hir_array
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell hashtables `@{key = value; ...}` map to a HIR
hashtable_literal whose "pairs" key holds a list of key_value_pair
HIRs (one per entry). Pairs are recursively translated through
translate_node so they preserve their key/value AST shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "hashtable_literal".
Iterates children (each a key-value pair AST), recursively
translates via translate_node, appends to pairs list. Stores pairs
under "pairs".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_hashtable_literal" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell hashtable @{} to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_hashtable be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_hashtable, "node_type", "hashtable_literal"

    Note: The parser stores hashtable entries as flat alternating children
    Note: (key0, value0, key1, value1, ...). Pair them up into key_value_pair
    Note: HIR nodes so the backend can emit each `key = value` entry.
    Let pairs be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let key_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let key_hir be proc translate_node with key_ast

        Let pair_hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with pair_hir, "node_type", "key_value_pair"
        proc set_dict_value with pair_hir, "key", key_hir

        Let value_index be i plus 1
        If value_index is less than child_count:
            Let value_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, value_index multiplied by 8
            Let value_hir be proc translate_node with value_ast
            proc set_dict_value with pair_hir, "value", value_hir
        End If

        proc list_append with pairs, pair_hir
        Set i to i plus 2
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_hashtable, "pairs", pairs

    Return hir_hashtable
End Process

@Reasoning:
A hashtable pair has exactly two children (key, value), both of
which may be arbitrary expressions. Position-based child storage
matches the parser's emission and keeps the HIR shape simple.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "key_value_pair".
If child_count > 0 takes children[0], translates via
translate_node, stores under "key". If > 1 takes children[8],
translates, stores under "value".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_key_value_pair" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell key-value pair (key = value) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_pair be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "node_type", "key_value_pair"

    Note: Key (first child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let key_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let key_hir be proc translate_node with key_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "key", key_hir
    End If

    Note: Value (second child)
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let value_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 8
        Let value_hir be proc translate_node with value_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "value", value_hir
    End If

    Return hir_pair
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell subexpressions `$(...)` evaluate a contained expression
in expression context (rather than command context). The wrapping
is preserved in the HIR so the backend can handle the
context-switch semantics correctly during round-trip emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "subexpression".
If child_count > 0 takes children[0], translates via
translate_node, stores under "body". Returns the dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_subexpression" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell subexpression $() to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_subexpr be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_subexpr, "node_type", "subexpression"

    Note: Expression body
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_subexpr, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_subexpr
End Process

@Reasoning:
A PowerShell type expression `[TypeName]` (used for casts `[int]$x`,
type checks, and parameter annotations) carries the type name as its
single AST_IDENTIFIER child. The HIR records the bracketed name under
"type_name" so the backend can re-emit `[TypeName]` verbatim and the
round-trip preserves the exact type token.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads children and child_count. Builds an HIR
dict tagged "type_expression". If child_count > 0 reads children[0]'s
value slot (offset 32) as the type-name lexeme and stores it under
"type_name".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_type_expression" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell type expression [TypeName] to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_type be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_type, "node_type", "type_expression"

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let name_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let name_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with name_ast, 32
        proc set_dict_value with hir_type, "type_name", name_value
    End If

    Return hir_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell uses word operators `-eq`, `-ne`, `-gt`, `-and`,
`-bor`, etc. plus traditional symbol operators. The operator
string is stored verbatim from offset 8 so the HIR preserves the
exact source form including the leading hyphen for word operators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads operator (offset 8). Builds HIR
dict tagged "binary_operation" with operator stored under
"operator". If child_count > 0 translates children[0] -> "left".
If > 1 translates children[8] -> "right".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_binary_operation" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell binary operations (-eq, -ne, -gt, etc.) to HIR

