@End Implementation
Process called "translate_method_definition" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell method definition to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_method be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "node_type", "method_definition"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "name", value

    Note: Parameters (all children except last)
    Let parameters be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    Let body_index be child_count minus 1

    While i is less than body_index:
        Let param_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let param_hir be proc translate_node with param_ast
        proc list_append with parameters, param_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "parameters", parameters

    Note: Body (last child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, body_index multiplied by 8
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_method
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell try-catch-finally is encoded with try-body first, then
any catch clauses, then optionally a finally block as the last
child. The translator uses position (child_count - 1) to identify
the finally block - it slices catches as children[1..finally-1]
and treats the last as finally only when child_count > 1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "try_statement".
If child_count > 0 translates children[0] -> "try_body". Computes
finally_index = child_count - 1. Iterates i = 1..finally_index-1,
calls translate_catch_clause on each, appends to catch_clauses
list under "catch_clauses". If child_count > 1, takes
children[finally_index], translates via translate_node, stores
under "finally_body" (note: this could be a catch clause if there
is no finally; the parser must place finally last by convention).
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_try_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell try-catch-finally to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_try be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_try, "node_type", "try_statement"

    Note: Try body (first child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let try_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let try_hir be proc translate_node with try_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_try, "try_body", try_hir
    End If

    Note: Catch clauses (middle children)
    Let catch_clauses be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 1
    Let finally_index be child_count minus 1

    While i is less than finally_index:
        Let catch_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let catch_hir be proc translate_catch_clause with catch_ast
        proc list_append with catch_clauses, catch_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_try, "catch_clauses", catch_clauses

    Note: Finally block (last child, optional)
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let finally_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, finally_index multiplied by 8
        Let finally_hir be proc translate_node with finally_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_try, "finally_body", finally_hir
    End If

    Return hir_try
End Process

@Reasoning:
A catch clause has optional exception type (first child),
optional variable name (second child, always a literal), and a
body (last child). The optional-but-required positional encoding
means the implementation treats the last child as body
unconditionally even when no type/variable is present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "catch_clause". If
child_count > 0 translates children[0] -> "exception_type". If >
1 takes children[8] through translate_literal -> "variable".
Computes body_index = child_count - 1. If child_count > 0
translates children[body_index] -> "body". Note this means a
catch with no type/variable still stores its body correctly
because body_index points to children[0].
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_catch_clause" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell catch clause to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_catch be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_catch, "node_type", "catch_clause"

    Note: Exception type (first child, optional)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let type_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let type_hir be proc translate_node with type_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_catch, "exception_type", type_hir
    End If

    Note: Variable name (second child, optional)
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let var_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 8
        Let var_hir be proc translate_literal with var_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_catch, "variable", var_hir
    End If

    Note: Body (last child)
    Let body_index be child_count minus 1
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, body_index multiplied by 8
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_catch, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_catch
End Process

@Reasoning:
`throw` and `throw $exception` differ only in whether an
expression child is present. Missing expression maps to absent
"expression" key for distinguishing bare rethrow from value-throw
positively.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "throw_statement".
If child_count > 0 translates children[0] -> "expression".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_throw_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell throw statement to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_throw be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_throw, "node_type", "throw_statement"

    Note: Exception expression (first child, optional)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let expr_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let expr_hir be proc translate_node with expr_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_throw, "expression", expr_hir
    End If

    Return hir_throw
End Process

@Reasoning:
`return` and `return value` differ only in whether a value child
is present. PowerShell functions also implicitly return their
last expression's value, but `return` itself is always explicit
in the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "return_statement".
If child_count > 0 translates children[0] -> "value".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_return_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell return statement to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_return be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_return, "node_type", "return_statement"

    Note: Return value (first child, optional)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let value_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let value_hir be proc translate_node with value_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_return, "value", value_hir
    End If

    Return hir_return
End Process

@Reasoning:
`break` is a control-flow marker - no children, no value. The HIR
just records its presence and the backend translates it to the
target language's break equivalent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds and returns an HIR dict with only
the "break_statement" tag.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_break_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell break statement to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_break be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_break, "node_type", "break_statement"

    Return hir_break
End Process

@Reasoning:
`continue` mirrors break: a tag-only marker that the backend
lowers to a jump-to-loop-condition. No children or value needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds and returns an HIR dict tagged
"continue_statement".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_continue_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell continue statement to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_continue be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_continue, "node_type", "continue_statement"

    Return hir_continue
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell `$var = value` always assigns to a variable (not an
arbitrary lvalue), so the first child is always a variable AST
and goes through translate_variable explicitly to ensure the HIR
has the expected variable_reference shape. The value side can
be any expression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "assignment". If
child_count > 0 takes children[0] through translate_variable ->
"variable". If > 1 takes children[8] through translate_node ->
"value".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_assignment" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell assignment ($var = value) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_assign be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "node_type", "assignment"

    Note: Variable (first child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let var_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let var_hir be proc translate_variable with var_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "variable", var_hir
    End If

    Note: Value (second child)
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let value_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 8
        Let value_hir be proc translate_node with value_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "value", value_hir
    End If

    Return hir_assign
End Process

@Reasoning:
Script blocks `{ statements }` are statement containers. The HIR
encodes them as script_block dicts with a statements list, the
same shape as the top-level script. The distinct _type lets the
printer wrap them in braces on emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Builds HIR dict tagged "script_block".
Iterates all children, recursively translates each via
translate_node, appends to statements list stored under
"statements".
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_block" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell script block {} to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_block be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_block, "node_type", "script_block"

    Let statements be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let stmt_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let stmt_hir be proc translate_node with stmt_ast
        proc list_append with statements, stmt_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_block, "statements", statements

    Return hir_block
End Process

@Reasoning:
The central dispatcher: reads the AST node's tag (offset 0) and
routes to the appropriate translate_* helper. Adding a new
PowerShell AST kind requires exactly one new arm here plus the
specialized translator. Literal tags 80-83 share a single
translate_literal entry handled by a range check at the bottom.
The range check is the only "fallthrough" pattern in this
dispatcher; everything else is one-tag-per-arm.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads node_type at offset 0. Cascading
ifs against constants: 1 -> translate_script, 3 -> pipeline, 10
-> if, 11 -> while, 12 -> for, 13 -> foreach, 14 -> switch, 20
-> function_definition, 21 -> assignment, 22 -> variable, 23 ->
class_definition, 24 -> property_definition, 25 ->
constructor_definition, 26 -> method_definition, 30 ->
try_statement, 31 -> catch_clause, 32 -> throw_statement, 33 ->
return_statement, 34 -> break_statement, 35 ->
continue_statement, 40 -> binary_operation, 41 ->
unary_operation, 42 -> member_access, 43 -> index_access, 44 ->
method_call, 70 -> cmdlet_invocation, 71 -> cmdlet, 72 ->
parameter, 73 -> array_literal, 74 -> hashtable_literal, 75 ->
key_value_pair, 76 -> subexpression, 77 -> block (script block).
Finally checks if node_type is in [80..83] and routes any of
those to translate_literal. Returns 0 for unrecognized tags.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_node" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main translation dispatcher for PowerShell AST nodes

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0

    Note: Dispatch is keyed on the parser's AST node constants
    Note: (powershell_parser.runa). Structural nodes route to their
    Note: dedicated translators; literals and identifiers route to
    Note: translate_literal which reads the lexeme from the node value slot.

    Note: AST_SCRIPT (1)
    If node_type is equal to 1:
        Return proc translate_script with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PIPELINE (3)
    If node_type is equal to 3:
        Return proc translate_pipeline with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_BLOCK (5)
    If node_type is equal to 5:
        Return proc translate_block with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_IF_STATEMENT (10)
    If node_type is equal to 10:
        Return proc translate_if_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_WHILE_STATEMENT (11)
    If node_type is equal to 11:
        Return proc translate_while_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_FOR_STATEMENT (12)
    If node_type is equal to 12:
        Return proc translate_for_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_FOREACH_STATEMENT (13)
    If node_type is equal to 13:
        Return proc translate_foreach_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_SWITCH_STATEMENT (14)
    If node_type is equal to 14:
        Return proc translate_switch_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_DO_WHILE (15) and AST_DO_UNTIL (16) share the while shape
    Note: (condition + body) at the HIR level.
    If node_type is equal to 15:
        Return proc translate_while_statement with ast
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 16:
        Return proc translate_while_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION (20), AST_FILTER_DEFINITION (21),
    Note: AST_WORKFLOW_DEFINITION (22) share the function shape.
    If node_type is equal to 20:
        Return proc translate_function_definition with ast
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 21:
        Return proc translate_function_definition with ast
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 22:
        Return proc translate_function_definition with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_CLASS_DEFINITION (23) and AST_ENUM_DEFINITION (24) both carry
    Note: a name child followed by member children.
    If node_type is equal to 23:
        Return proc translate_class_definition with ast
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 24:
        Return proc translate_class_definition with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_METHOD_DEFINITION (25)
    If node_type is equal to 25:
        Return proc translate_method_definition with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PROPERTY_DEFINITION (26)
    If node_type is equal to 26:
        Return proc translate_property_definition with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PARAM_BLOCK (30) — a list of AST_PARAMETER children.
    If node_type is equal to 30:
        Return proc translate_block with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PARAMETER (31)
    If node_type is equal to 31:
        Return proc translate_parameter with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_VARIABLE (32)
    If node_type is equal to 32:
        Return proc translate_variable with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_VARIABLE_ASSIGNMENT (33)
    If node_type is equal to 33:
        Return proc translate_assignment with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PROPERTY_ACCESS (34)
    If node_type is equal to 34:
        Return proc translate_member_access with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_METHOD_CALL (35)
    If node_type is equal to 35:
        Return proc translate_method_call with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_ARRAY_ACCESS (36)
    If node_type is equal to 36:
        Return proc translate_index_access with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_BINARY_EXPRESSION (40)
    If node_type is equal to 40:
        Return proc translate_binary_operation with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_UNARY_EXPRESSION (41)
    If node_type is equal to 41:
        Return proc translate_unary_operation with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_SUBEXPRESSION (42)
    If node_type is equal to 42:
        Return proc translate_subexpression with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_ARRAY_SUBEXPRESSION (43)
    If node_type is equal to 43:
        Return proc translate_array_literal with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_HASHTABLE (44)
    If node_type is equal to 44:
        Return proc translate_hashtable_literal with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_ARRAY_LITERAL (45)
    If node_type is equal to 45:
        Return proc translate_array_literal with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_TYPE_EXPRESSION (46) — translates as the bracketed type name.
    If node_type is equal to 46:
        Return proc translate_type_expression with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_TRY_STATEMENT (50)
    If node_type is equal to 50:
        Return proc translate_try_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_CATCH_STATEMENT (51)
    If node_type is equal to 51:
        Return proc translate_catch_clause with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_FINALLY_STATEMENT (52) — body-only clause.
    If node_type is equal to 52:
        Return proc translate_catch_clause with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_THROW_STATEMENT (53)
    If node_type is equal to 53:
        Return proc translate_throw_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_RETURN_STATEMENT (60)
    If node_type is equal to 60:
        Return proc translate_return_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_BREAK_STATEMENT (61)
    If node_type is equal to 61:
        Return proc translate_break_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_CONTINUE_STATEMENT (62)
    If node_type is equal to 62:
        Return proc translate_continue_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_EXIT_STATEMENT (63) — modelled as a return with optional value.
    If node_type is equal to 63:
        Return proc translate_return_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_IDENTIFIER (70) — name-carrying leaf; lexeme under "value".
    If node_type is equal to 70:
        Return proc translate_literal with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_CMDLET (71) — cmdlet invocation: name in the value slot, args
    Note: and named parameters as children.
    If node_type is equal to 71:
        Return proc translate_cmdlet_invocation with ast
    End If

    Note: Literal leaves: AST_STRING_LITERAL (72), AST_NUMBER_LITERAL (73),
    Note: AST_BOOLEAN_LITERAL (74), AST_NULL_LITERAL (75).
    If node_type is greater than or equal to 72:
        If node_type is less than or equal to 75:
            Return proc translate_literal with ast
        End If
    End If

    Note: AST_SWITCH_CLAUSE (80) and AST_DEFAULT_CLAUSE (82)
    If node_type is equal to 80:
        Return proc translate_switch_case with ast
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 82:
        Return proc translate_switch_case with ast
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The PowerShell program root translates to an HIR script dict
whose "statements" key holds every top-level statement's HIR.
Distinct _type "script" (vs "script_block") lets downstream
consumers recognize the program root.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null ast. Reads children and child_count. Builds
HIR dict tagged "script". Iterates children, recursively
translates via translate_node, appends to a statements list
stored under "statements". Returns the script dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_script" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate PowerShell script (top-level) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24

    Let hir_script be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_script, "node_type", "script"

    Let statements be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let stmt_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let stmt_hir be proc translate_node with stmt_ast
        proc list_append with statements, stmt_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_script, "statements", statements

    Return hir_script
End Process

@Reasoning:
The public entry simply forwards into translate_node, which is the generic AST
dispatch function. The single-line body is intentional: we want one well-known
exported symbol that other modules can wire into the translation registry, but
we do not want to duplicate the per-node-kind logic that translate_node already
contains. Anything PowerShell-specific (cmdlet recognition, parameter binding,
pipeline desugaring, object-oriented constructs) is decided inside
translate_node's dispatch table - keeping the entry trivial lets us add new
node kinds without ever touching this function.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_powershell_to_hir" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main translation entry point for PowerShell AST to HIR

    Return proc translate_node with ast
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Source-Level Translation Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end source convenience entry for the PowerShell frontend,
mirroring c_to_hir_from_source: it owns the full lex + parse + lower
pipeline so the central translation dispatcher can route PowerShell
source text straight to a HIR root with a single call. The PowerShell
lexer entry (tokenize) takes the source pointer AND its byte length -
PowerShell scans by absolute position against a known end, so the length
must be supplied; it is computed once with StringCore.string_length.
tokenize builds the lexer, scans the whole source into the lexer's
token buffer, and returns the lexer record (tokens stored at lexer
offsets 40/48). create_parser then reads that token buffer off the lexer
and primes its index. The PowerShell parser records a sticky error flag
at offset 32 (set on a mandatory-token mismatch); there is no accessor
process, so the flag is read directly with memory_get_int64, and a
nonzero value means the AST is partial so the wrapper returns 0 rather
than lowering a malformed tree. The lexer and parser are arena-backed
records with no per-instance destructors in this frontend (matching the
file's existing tokenize/create_parser design), so the wrapper performs
no manual teardown - their storage is reclaimed with the surrounding
arena, and the HIR built by translate_powershell_to_hir is independent
of those records. Returning 0 on any null intermediate or on a parse
error matches Runa's nullable-pointer convention and the dispatcher's
documented "0 means frontend failed" contract.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Null-guard source (return 0). Compute the source byte length with
string_length(source). tokenize(source, length) scans the source and
returns the lexer carrying its token buffer; return 0 if it fails.
create_parser(lexer) reads the token buffer and primes the parser index;
return 0 on failure. parse_script(parser) walks the token stream to a
PowerShell AST root; return 0 on a null root. Read the sticky has_error
flag at parser offset 32 via memory_get_int64: if nonzero, return 0.
Otherwise lower the AST with translate_powershell_to_hir(ast) and return
the resulting HIR root.
@End Implementation
Process called "powershell_to_hir_from_source" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Let lexer be proc tokenize from Lexer with source, length
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_script from Parser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parse_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32
    If parse_error is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_powershell_to_hir with ast

    Return hir
End Process

Note: End of PowerShell→HIR Translator